<p>IB 200B focuses on the use of an historical framework in answering ecological
and evolutionary questions.&nbsp; This course covers the many applications
of phylogenetics to ecology, behavior, development, functional morphology,
populational genetics, conservation, biogeogeography, and speciation that
are revolutionizing those fields.&nbsp; Labs are closely integrated with
lectures and cover the major algorithms and software.&nbsp; Requirements
include participation in discussion, two exams, and a term project. This
project is an important practical experience; we allow (in fact, encourage)
students to focus on organisms that they are studying for their thesis
or other research.
<p>IB 200B is taught every other Spring semester and alternates with IB
200A "Principles of Phylogenetics: Systematics." Both are meant for graduate
students and advanced undergraduates.&nbsp; IB 200A covers the core theory
and methodology for comparative biology: phylogenetic analysis with emphases
on both morphology and molecules, and both living and fossil organisms--to
be offered spring 2000! Check it out.
